What happens during future Mail Server builds

A future mail1 will:

Obtain Docker CE RPMs from the Repo VM.
Obtain the pinned Mailcow source archive from the Repo VM.
Obtain the compressed image bundle over the LAN.
Verify all SHA-256 checksums.
Install Docker without using the public Docker repository.
Load all Mailcow images locally.
Verify every image ID.
Generate mailcow.conf.
Start Mailcow with public image pulls disabled.

The generated installer will be available at:
http://repo.corp.local/manifests/mailcow/current/install-mailcow-offline.sh

A typical future Mail VM command will be:
 curl -fsSLo install-mailcow-offline.sh \
  http://repo.corp.local/manifests/mailcow/current/install-mailcow-offline.sh

chmod +x install-mailcow-offline.sh

sudo bash ./install-mailcow-offline.sh \
  --hostname mail1.internal.local \
  --timezone Asia/Kolkata \
  --disable-firewalld \
  --start

Expected time benefit

The first stage-three build will still take time because the Repo VM must download everything once.

After that:

Public Internet image download       Eliminated on new Mail VMs
Public GitHub source download        Eliminated on new Mail VMs
Public Docker RPM download           Eliminated on new Mail VMs
Repeated container registry pulls    Eliminated
Transfer source                       Repo VM → Mail VM over LAN
Transfer image bundle                 Repo VM → Mail VM over LAN
Docker image loading                  Still required locally

The image bundle may still be several gigabytes, so LAN transfer and docker image load will take some time. However, deployment becomes predictable and no longer depends on Docker Hub/GHCR speed, rate limits, Internet latency, or repeated downloads.

Storage recommendation

The package enforces minimum free-space gates of:

Repository/staging space : 24 GiB
Docker data space        : 16 GiB

When /srv/repo and /var/lib/docker are on the same filesystem, those requirements effectively combine. For retained releases and safe staging, provision approximately:

60–80 GiB free space or more

